r threat. Identifying such paranoia as emerging from an increasingly disjunctive relation between this conception of the subject and the changing nature of the public sphere, she develops the concept of the paranoid chronotope as a tool for the theoretical analysis of social, literary, and critical practices today. Investigating twenty-first century paranoid fictions, New Sincerity novels, conspiracist online culture, and postcritique, Beckman shows how the paranoid chronotope constitutes a recurring feature of modern consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony21st centuryxThemes, motives. 0aCritical theoryzUnited States. 0aNeoliberalismzUnited States. 0aParanoia in literature. 0aParanoiaxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSocial psychologyzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aParanoia.  aidentity.  apostcritique.  aposttruth.  apower.  athe paranoid chronotope.  athe public sphere.  awhite masculinity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2022 Englishz978311099370708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2022z9783110993684oZDB-23-DSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363161840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631618/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099370-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2022 Englishb